        "trailText":"The government has been <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/oct/15/government-cut-balls-off-elderly-social-care-scheme\" title=\"\">accused of backtracking on a promise </a>that elderly people will not have to sell their homes to pay for long-term care but why has it become such a hot political issue?",
        "headline":"Social care for the elderly – key questions answered",
        "body":"<h2>What's the row all about?</h2><p>At the heart of the matter is the debate over who should pay for someone who moves into a care home because they can no longer look after themselves. Successive governments have been trying to establish how much the state and the individual should pay, particularly if the person receiving care owns a house they could sell or substantial savings. About 40,000 people a year are forced to sell their homes to pay care home bills. The question has become a hot political issue, with strong feelings on both sides of the argument. This only affects those in England. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2008/apr/29/longtermcare.socialcare\" title=\"\">Scotland has a different system of free personal care for elderly people.</a></p><p></p><h2>What was proposed in the care bill?</h2><p>The Oxford economist Andrew Dilnot's <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2011/jul/04/elderly-care-proposals-dinot-report\" title=\"\">commission into the funding of long-term care originally recommended</a> that a cap of between £23,000 and £50,000 (with a suggested figure of £35,000) should be placed on the costs of long-term care. This would be the most an individual should pay for their care.</p><p>His report has loosely formed the basis for the bill going through parliament.</p><p>The government decided it could not afford his proposal and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/feb/10/inheritance-tax-freeze-social-care\" title=\"\">instead set the cap at £75,000 </a>on the grounds that a lower figure would be too costly. The bill's aim is to give people a clear figure to enable them to plan for their old age. The cap only covers care costs. If you are in residential care you will be expected to contribute towards your \"hotel\" costs, such as food and accommodation, as you would if you were living in your own home.</p><p>Dilnot originally also suggested a universal deferred payment scheme to reduce the number of older people forced to sell their homes to pay for care. Councils would pay the costs and recoup them once the house was sold, usually after the person in care had died.</p><p>This was to stop people having to make distressed sales of homes at a time of great uncertainty as they were moving into a care home.</p><p></p><h2>So what's changed?</h2><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/oct/15/government-cut-balls-off-elderly-social-care-scheme\" title=\"\">Lord Lipsey says the government has moved the goalposts</a> by quietly inserting a new clause that would mean the deferred payments scheme would not be available if the person held any assets of £23,250 or above. He says that because many older people have savings above this level, they will in effect have to either spend their savings down to below £23,250, or be forced to sell their homes, just as before.</p><p>He and others have since said this could kill the bill in its current form as few Tory MPs in particular will vote for such a scheme.</p><p></p><h2>What's the government saying? </h2><p>A spokeswoman for the Department of Health said its aim is to legislate to ensure that every council in the country puts in place a scheme to allow people to defer payment of care home bills. \"The fine details, as you would expect, are being consulted on now, but we are clear that this will deliver on the promise that people will not be forced to sell their home in their lifetime to pay for care.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420043127|2013-10-16T12:07:39Z|28f26d1f023029663bf245b674cfe74196baaaf8 -->",
