        "trailText":"<p>Chief inspector of adult social care plans to make services more user-focused and give inspection system a 'fresh start'</p>",
        "headline":"CQC considers  using hidden cameras to monitor services",
        "body":"<p>The Care Quality Commission's chief inspector of adult social care has said the regulatory body will discuss using \"mystery shoppers\" and hidden cameras to monitor care services in future.</p><p>Andrea Sutcliffe, who was appointed to the role in July, pointed out that the media have already used such methods to draw attention to substandard care in documentaries such as the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2011/jun/01/panorama-care-home-abuse-investigation-government-review?guni=Article:in%20body%20link\" title=\"\">BBC Panorama expose</a> on Winterbourne View care home in Bristol in 2011.</p><p>However, Sutcliffe, who was previously chief executive of the Social Care Institute for Excellence, said the CQC had to \"consider the privacy and dignity of people receiving care\" and that the decision to do so would not be taken lightly.</p><p>Sutcliffe's paper, which outlines her priorities for transforming the inspection and monitoring of care services, is focused on working more closely with care service users. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/social-care-network/2013/jul/19/chief-inspector-adult-social-care\" title=\"\">Writing for the Social Care Network</a> on her appointment to the CQC in July, shesaid her top priority would be \"working with and on the side of people who use services, their families and carers\".</p><p>Other changes include <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/oct/14/care-home-inspection-reforms\" title=\"\">recruiting a team of \"experts by experience</a>\" – users of care services, their relatives and other \"advocates\" who would assist in inspecting care providers.  Under these propsals, a standard inspection team would consist of an inspector from the expert inspection team, a user expert and, where necessary, a specialist adviser relating to a particular area of concern. Sutcliffe said about 300 experts by experience had already been recruited, but that the CQC would need to \"at least double\" this amount if the idea was to be rolled out across the inspection system.</p><p>In what she described as a \"fresh start\" for care service inspections, a new rating system has also been introduced. Social care providers will now be rated as outstanding, good, requires improvement or inadequate. Inspections will be based on five key requirements: assessing whether care services are safe, caring, effective, well-led and responsive to people's needs. Sutcliffe also said that services rated outstanding or good might be subject to random inspections ahead of the time when they were expecting them, to reduce the risk of complacency.</p><p>Stricter monitoring of care providers is another feature of Sutcliffe's plans. From April 2015, and subject to the care bill becoming law, the CQC will monitor the finances of 50 to 60 larger care providers who would be difficult to replace if they were to go out of business. There will also be more rigorous analysis of applications to offer care services, which Sutcliffe's report says will \"make sure providers have the right values and motivations for providing care\".</p><p>The CQC will also aim to forge closer partnerships with other organisations, in particular local <a href=\"http://www.healthwatch.co.uk/\" title=\"\">HealthWatch</a> bodies, with the aim of collecting more detailed data on care providers. Providers will also be encouraged to share their data with the CQC.</p><p>A full public consultation will be held on Sutcliffe's proposals in spring 2014.</p><p><strong>Why not join our </strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/social-care\" title=\"\"><strong>social care </strong></a><strong>community? Becoming a member of the Guardian </strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/social-care-network\" title=\"\"><strong>Social Care Network</strong></a><strong> means you get sent weekly email updates on </strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/social-care-network/policy\" title=\"\"><strong>policy</strong></a><strong> and best practice in the sector, as well as exclusive offers. </strong><a href=\"https://register.theguardian.com/social-care/\" title=\"\"><strong>Sign up for free here</strong></a><strong>. </strong></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419914721|2013-10-16T12:07:39Z|66cce3535a234a1b61369b9a91081890b4ed210c -->",
